  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How is a Roth IRA conversion taxed?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The amount you convert from a traditional IRA or 401(k) to a Roth IRA is added to your ordinary income in the year of conversion and taxed at your regular federal income tax rates. There is no special capital gains rate for conversions. If the conversion pushes you into a higher bracket, only the income in that bracket is taxed at the higher rate due to the progressive tax system."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "When does a Roth IRA conversion make sense?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A Roth conversion tends to make the most sense when your current tax rate is lower than you expect your rate to be in retirement, when you have years of tax-free growth ahead, when you have cash outside the IRA to pay the conversion tax, or when you expect to leave the account to heirs who would benefit from tax-free withdrawals."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is there an income limit for Roth IRA conversions?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. There is no income limit for Roth IRA conversions. Anyone can convert a traditional IRA or eligible retirement account to a Roth IRA regardless of their income level. This is different from direct Roth IRA contributions, which are phased out at higher incomes."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does a Roth conversion affect Medicare premiums (IRMAA)?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. A large Roth conversion raises your modified adjusted gross income in the conversion year. Medicare uses MAGI from two years prior to set Part B and Part D premiums. If your MAGI crosses an IRMAA threshold, you will pay higher Medicare premiums two years after the conversion. In 2025, surcharges begin at $106,000 MAGI for single filers and $212,000 for married filing jointly."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the pro-rata rule and how does it affect a Roth conversion?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The pro-rata rule requires that any conversion be treated as coming proportionally from your pre-tax and after-tax IRA balances combined across all traditional, SEP, and SIMPLE IRAs. You cannot selectively convert only after-tax money. If you have $90,000 pre-tax and $10,000 after-tax in IRAs, then 90% of any conversion is taxable regardless of which account the money comes from."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Should I pay the Roth conversion tax from the IRA or from outside funds?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Pay the tax from outside funds if at all possible. If you withhold from the converted amount itself to pay the tax and you are under 59.5, the withheld portion is treated as a taxable distribution and subject to the 10% early withdrawal penalty. Even if you are over 59.5, using outside cash preserves more money inside the Roth for tax-free growth."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
  </script>
