      <div class="faq-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">FAQ</div>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">How is a Roth IRA conversion taxed?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">The amount you convert is added to your ordinary income in the year of conversion and taxed at your standard federal income tax rates. There is no special rate for conversions. Because the tax system is progressive, the conversion amount is only taxed at higher rates to the extent it pushes your income into higher brackets.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Is there an income limit for Roth conversions?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">No. There is no income limit for Roth IRA conversions. Anyone with a traditional IRA or eligible employer plan can convert to a Roth IRA regardless of income. This is different from direct Roth IRA contributions, which are phased out at higher MAGI levels ($150,000 to $165,000 for single filers in 2025).</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Should I pay the conversion tax from the IRA or from outside funds?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Pay the tax from outside funds if at all possible. If you withhold from the converted amount itself to pay the tax and you are under 59.5, the withheld portion is treated as a taxable distribution and subject to the 10% early withdrawal penalty. Even if you are over 59.5, using outside cash preserves more money inside the Roth for tax-free growth.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Can I undo a Roth conversion?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">No. The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 permanently eliminated recharacterization (reversing) of Roth conversions. Once you convert, the tax is owed and the conversion cannot be undone. Plan your conversion amounts carefully before executing.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What is the backdoor Roth IRA?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">The backdoor Roth is a strategy for high earners who exceed the Roth contribution income limits. They make a non-deductible traditional IRA contribution (which has no income limit) and then immediately convert it to a Roth. If done cleanly with no pre-existing traditional IRA balance, the conversion creates little or no taxable income. This strategy is legal under current law but should be executed carefully to avoid the pro-rata rule.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Does a Roth conversion count toward my Roth contribution limit?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">No. Roth conversions are separate from annual Roth contribution limits. In 2025 you can contribute up to $7,000 ($8,000 if 50 or older) directly to a Roth IRA if your income qualifies. You can also convert any amount from traditional accounts on top of that. They do not count against each other.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Does a Roth conversion affect Medicare premiums (IRMAA)?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Yes. A large Roth conversion raises your modified adjusted gross income (MAGI) in the conversion year. Medicare uses MAGI from two years prior to set Part B and Part D premiums. If your MAGI crosses an IRMAA threshold, you will pay higher Medicare premiums two years after the conversion year. In 2025, surcharges begin at $106,000 MAGI for single filers and $212,000 for married filing jointly. This is an often-overlooked cost that can add $600 to $6,000 or more annually in premium surcharges depending on income level.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What is the pro-rata rule and how does it affect my conversion?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">The pro-rata rule requires that any conversion be treated as coming proportionally from your pre-tax and after-tax IRA balances. If you have $90,000 in a traditional IRA (pre-tax) and $10,000 in non-deductible contributions (after-tax), then 90% of any conversion is taxable regardless of which dollars you think you are converting. You cannot selectively convert just the after-tax money. The rule applies across all your traditional, SEP, and SIMPLE IRAs combined -- not per account.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Can I do a Roth conversion from a 401(k) instead of an IRA?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Yes, if your employer plan allows in-service withdrawals or you have separated from your employer. A direct rollover from a 401(k) to a Roth IRA is a conversion and is taxed the same way -- the pre-tax amount rolled over is added to your ordinary income. One important difference: 401(k) balances are not included in the pro-rata calculation for IRA conversions, which is why some people roll traditional IRA money back into a 401(k) before doing a backdoor Roth to avoid the pro-rata rule.</div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
        <h2>Related Calculators and Guides</h2>
